ss look at three national cases -- tPart 3: Assessment -- t18 Evaluating citizens' assemblies: Criteria, methods and tools -- t19 Internal dynamics at work -- t20 Citizens' assemblies and their effects on the population -- t21 The impact of citizens' assemblies on policymaking: Approaches and methods -- t22 Citizens' assemblies in authoritarian regimes: China, Cuba, and Libya -- tPart 4: Different perceptions of citizens' assemblies -- t23 Citizens' support for citizens' assemblies -- t24 How do elected officials perceive deliberative citizens' assemblies? -- t25 The deliberative public servants: The roles of public servants in citizens' assemblies -- t26 Populists and citizens' assemblies: Caught between strategy and principles? -- t27 Citizens' assemblies and communication studies -- t28 Social movements and citizens' assemblies -- tPart 5: Conclusion -- t29 Citizens' assemblies: Beyond utopian and dystopian approaches -- tIndex0 aOpen Accessuhttps://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_abf2funrestricted online access2star  aCitizens' Assemblies (CAs) are flourishing around the world. Quite often composed of randomly selected citizens, CAs, arguably, come as a possible answer to contemporary democratic challenges. Democracies worldwide are indeed confronted with a series of disruptive phenomena such as a widespread perception of distrust and growing polarization as well as low performance. Many actors seek to reinvigorate democracy with citizen participation and deliberation. CAs are expected to have the potential to meet this twofold objective. But, despite deliberative and inclusive qualities of CAs, many questions remain open. The increasing popularity of CAs call for a holistic reflection and evaluation on their origins, current uses and future directions. The De Gruyter Handbook of Citizens' Assemblies showcases the state of the art around the study of CAs and opens novel perspectives informed by multidisciplinary research and renewed thinking about deliberative participatory processes. It discusses the latest theoretical, empirical, and methodological scientific developments on CAs and offers a unique resource for scholars, decision-makers, practitioners, and curious citizens to better understand the qualities, purposes, promises but also pitfalls of CAs.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0 uhttps://www.degruyter.com/dg/page/open-access-policy  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 4aBürgerbeteiligung. 4aDeliberative Demokratie. 4aMini-publics. 4aPolitische Theorie. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Political ideologies / Democracy.2bisacsh  adeliberative democracy, mini-publics, citizen participation, political theory.1 aBoswell, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBottin, Jehan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBussu, Sonia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCaluwaerts, Didier, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChaguaceda, Armando, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCurato, Nicole, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aElstub, Stephen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aErcan, Selen A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFarrell, David M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFelicetti, Andrea, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFiket, Irena, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFleuß, Dannica, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGeissel, Brigitte, econtr